/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ferdnyc/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ferdnyc/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ferdnyc/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ferdnyc/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ferdnyc/received_events","type":"User","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2025-09-11T06:06:55Z","updated_at":"2025-09-11T06:06:55Z","body":"@sterliakov Hm, displaying URLs in `--help` isn't too common, so I'm having trouble coming up with other examples of that.\n\nFor tools that display URLs in man pages, fixed-wrapping text files, etc., they typically just ensure the whole URL gets printed as a contiguous string, even if it's required to exceed their normal line length. (It'll get wrapped by the terminal, if it's longer than that width.)\n\nA wrapped URL will still be recognized as such, if it's otherwise unbroken.\n\nIOW, in an 80-column-wide terminal, this will be parsed as a complete url:\n\n```console\n# 345678901234567890123456789012345678901234567890123456789012345678901234567890\n$ echo \"https://mypy.readthedocs.io/en/stable/kinds_of_types.html#optional-types-and-the-none-type\"\nhttps://mypy.readthedocs.io/en/stable/kinds_of_types.html#optional-types-and-the\n-none-type\n```\nBoth of these will get cut off at the newline:\n\n```console\n# 345678901234567890123456789012345678901234567890123456789012345678901234567890\n$ echo \"https://mypy.readthedocs.io/en/stable/kinds_of_types.html#optional-types-and-the\\n-none-type\"\nhttps://mypy.readthedocs.io/en/stable/kinds_of_types.html#optional-types-and-the\n-none-type\n$ echo \"https://mypy.readthedocs.io/en/stable/kinds_of_types.html#optional-types-and-the\\n  -none-type\"\nhttps://mypy.readthedocs.io/en/stable/kinds_of_types.html#optional-types-and-the\n  -none-type\n```\n\nAs long as the _terminal_ (not the program) is doing the wrapping, it's OK.\n","author_associat